{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17607114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17607114"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:21:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:21:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15950"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15950"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.42,0.3,0.25,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8641"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63310"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8641"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15950"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48761"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1870"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"5323"},{"type":"tags","id":"8629"},{"type":"tags","id":"9847"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20688"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20693"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63310"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring fetal development, the ductus arteriosus serves as a vital vascular connection that allows most of the blood from the right ventricle to bypass the lungs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the normal physiological closure of the ductus arteriosus after birth?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased oxygen tension causes smooth muscle contraction","Increased prostaglandin E2 causes vessel constriction","Reduced pulmonary vascular resistance triggers closure","Inflammatory cells actively degrade the vessel wall","Increased carbon dioxide levels cause vasoconstriction"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ductus arteriosus closes in two phases:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFunctional closure occurs within 24-48 hours after birth due to smooth muscle contraction triggered by:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased oxygen tension\u003C/strong\u003E after birth triggers smooth muscle contraction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDecreased prostaglandin E2 levels\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnatomical closure occurs over several weeks through tissue remodelling\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other proposed mechanisms are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased prostaglandin E2\u003C/strong\u003E actually maintains ductal patency and does not cause constriction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced pulmonary vascular resistance\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after birth but is not the primary trigger for ductal closure\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory cells\u003C/strong\u003E are not involved in the initial functional closure\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased carbon dioxide\u003C/strong\u003E levels do not directly affect ductal closure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding ductal closure is clinically important. In infants with duct-dependent congenital heart disease, prostaglandin E2 can be administered to maintain ductal patency until corrective surgery. Conversely, in premature infants with symptomatic patent ductus arteriosus, cyclooxygenase inhibitors like indomethacin can be used to promote closure by reducing prostaglandin synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ductus arteriosus connects the pulmonary trunk to the aorta during fetal life and normally closes within 24-48 hours after birth.","Prostaglandin E2 maintains patency of the ductus arteriosus during fetal life.","Increased oxygen tension and decreased prostaglandin levels after birth trigger closure of the ductus arteriosus."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Dice JE, Bhatia J. Patent ductus arteriosus: an overview. J Pediatr Pharmacol Ther. 2007 Jul;12(3):138-46. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3462096/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48761"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15950"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48761"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T13:11:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T13:12:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8641"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63310"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic